Delta State government has expressed concern over the increasing number of divorce cases, saying the state has recorded no fewer than 156 divorce proceedings in the first quarter of 2020. The chief judge of the state, Justice Marshall Umukoro who gave the figure yesterday during his visit to Kwale Custodial Centre announced the release of 42 awaiting trial inmates following the review of their cases. Justice Umukoro appealed to Nigerians to respect the marriage institution as the high rates of broken marriages and bad upbringing of children were significantly contributing to the high incidence of crimes by youths in the society. Justice Umukoro said many marriage institutions have been in trouble and broken homes have contributed to the high incidence of crimes by the youth in the society, urging Nigerians to respect the marriage institutions no matter the situation as the only way to reduce the upsurge in crimes among the youths. “In the first quarter of 2020, the state recorded 156 divorce proceedings and this is not good at all”, he said, adding that the high number of youths awaiting trial at Kwale Custodial Centre showed that many parents had contributed to the bad upbringing of their children.   